Food Debt to European Inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, the inflation rate was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the Leitzins. In its discretion, the rate cut would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment to create an inflationary spiral.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below 2%, or at least close to the 2% mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in doubt: inflation must be "agreed" to rule out the need for action later.
With 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Responsible for the rise in inflation in the eurozone are the rise in food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat quotations rose 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in the price of edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup's government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably by the beginning of December, with the party having the largest base camp for the first time since 2002, while, according to Gallup, the approval for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent.
The difference is clear among the party loyal voters thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: More than two-thirds (71 percent) are opposed to a fifth (20 percent) of the MSZP’s approval.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry barrier: they come to two percent in the total population.
The number of party voters in both camps has grown by one percent.
Compared to the last low, the general economic sentiment has deteriorated further -- never before has the proportion of those who judge the country's economic situation to be "extremely bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it to be "relatively bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only a tenth expects improvement.
A Gallup survey conducted in December found that 71% of respondents — a historic high — rated the Prime Minister’s work as “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of respondents have high confidence or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the share of supporters for Viktor Orbán accounts for 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared to 27% distrust the head of Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of those who think that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister could be addressed even without a change of government.
If, after the unrest last October, 35% had voted in favour of the government and the head of government, this proportion today amounts to only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would participate "with certainty", and another 20 percent would vote "probably".
In comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place on this Sunday, only 55 percent would "certainly" go to the polls, and another 15 percent would consider their participation "probable". Given these trends, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital day allowance.
Turning to the group of those who participated in the referendum "with certainty", the shares of the opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would even be 81, 84, and 89 percent, respectively.
Auchan most expensive, Tesco increased by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trading area have again this year maintained the average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no increase in VAT this year.
Articles from Napi Gazdaság
In the Budaörs trading triangle, the price of the usual Christmas basket of the "Napi" has also increased by 16 percent this year, but price increases of over HUF 1,000 have been recorded in all hypermarkets.
After prices in the food markets "galopped" last December, the inflation rate has not been drastic in percentage terms, compared to the already high, earlier baseline level.
However, it is certainly deterrent to consumers that what they had paid for last year is not even available for HUF 10,000 this year.
The price of the "Napi" shopping cart exceeded the magical 10,000 HUF limit by at least 91 HUF in the surveyed markets.
The highest price was HUF 10,573.
(In 6800, the price was HUF 6,800.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at the same level as last year, while prices for turkey breast fillets, nuts and poppy rose sharply.
Prices for flour and bread corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary, but at Auchan there were 1kg of breadwaves for 139 forints.
There was no competitive fall in the price of the product to less than 200 forints.
Also surprising was the price of a two-liter Coca-Cola deposit bottle of less than 200 forints, so the drink, including the deposit, cost only HUF 257.
Nevertheless, this year's "Napi" shopping cart comparison saw Auchan the most expensive, and Cora the most favorable.
Our calculations have shown that Cora's prices in the "Napi" basket compared to last year's Christmas prices have increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan have increased by 18 percent each.
The difference between the cheapest shopping cart of the previous year and the most expensive of this year was 12%, while the increase between the cheapest shopping cart of the previous year and the most expensive of the current year was 21%.
The average price increase was HUF 1,480.00.
The average price increase in the previous year was still 1,206.00 forint, but the VAT increase in prices last Christmas was noticeable.
It is precisely this process that hit the trade: it seems that the department stores were not quite able to decide which price range to apply to the individual articles, since the effects of the price increase on consumer behaviour were unforeseeable.
(If the retailer badly plans a product’s speed of circulation, it can fall by substantial gains in the price range that depends on the traffic intensity.)
Due to VAT, the cost of the "Napi" basket was so radical last year that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 forints, while the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 forints.
This year, such extremes were not observed, as the most expensive basket cost 1,630.00 forints more than the previous year, and even at the cheapest there was a price increase of 1,284.00 forints.
Compared to the last two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic price increase, with the price of daily consumables in hypermarkets rising by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily confirm the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary: for some basic foodstuffs, the Statistical Office observed an increase of more than 30% over the 12-month period.
In addition to flour, there are also eggs.)
However, if you take a look at the "Napi" shopping cart, this seems almost impossible with the latter, since the price level of the already in the previous year expensive product has risen by little more than 10 percent, even in the worst case.
Obviously, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than the egg suppliers - after all, they were able to revolve the drastic price increase on the multis.
In the golden trading triangle, the hypermarkets do not complain; it is continuously reported of good years.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer look at prices at all.
Large quantities of everything are purchased, durable foods go into pallets over the counters.
Wednesday morning there were endless queues at the cash desk in all three department stores, when suddenly the number of customers exploded.
However, the country is reporting a lower customer frequency, so many multis complain to opinion researchers that they could not even achieve the planned turnover, not only in food, but also in sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overloading of staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to curbing infections, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János hospital, an MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1094 infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without it causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or applied improperly, the well-responsive bacteria develop antibiotic-resistant, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA just does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - according to Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rarely
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for curbing the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and retirement homes, hospitals should examine the hospitalized patients and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
However, in Hungarian hospitals microbiological sampling is not practiced as often.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the agent can develop, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals either.
Among outpatients, or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Savings on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted from one patient to another by nursing staff.
It is precisely for this reason that washing hands, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the home hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds tightly lined together, although from an epidemiological point of view, there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the less well-off hospitals, there are even savings in disinfectants, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that directly favor the development of infections.
Such infections are shown to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs to health insurance companies, so they are being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
After the first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the prevention of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
