Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe looks closely at the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who buys in the EU’s still cheapest market, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most sought-after patch for real estate purchases in the Eastern European region, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains are the Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa regions among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "gold coast", the "sun coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but properties around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will sooner or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favourable area of Russe has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offers the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfing paradises, and thus attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons as well in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking a change in their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while at the Black Sea and in the ski resorts there are predominantly Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down either buy revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or downturned houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication opportunities are of great importance, but the proximity to a major city, shops and doctors are also crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of increasing their value in the medium to long term.
However, real estate in the capital is becoming increasingly expensive due to the ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are at their lowest levels in Bulgaria, but over the past five years there has been an annual price increase of 21 percent.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiration of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a heated debate between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signalled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but it would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question at the conference is whether the industrialized countries are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement has also been reached on assisting developing countries.
The adaptation fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member council, likely at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be found in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s commitment to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that by 2020, the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether the "after 2012 agreement" will be achieved successfully or not. The Union would even be willing to work for a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialized countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to meet their commitments in an effort and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its 15 member states at the time, had already pledged a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be read in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a renewed international emission reduction system, whose importance has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific report of the UN Committee on Climate Change, which has been awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay emission reductions, and an increase in Earth’s average temperature of more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertises on YouTube
British Army units have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Since March 2006, special forces stationed in Afghanistan have uploaded videos about operations conducted against the Taliban, the BBC reports.
The miniature shots with helmet-mounted cameras are checked at the Air Force Base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are put on the Internet.
The political message is unavoidable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under “defenceheadquarters” in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Foreign Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of foreign operations.
Such published propaganda is virtually free compared to traditional television advertisements, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur recordings, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored recordings, also make it onto the net - such as those that show the deaths of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, at most, the losses are talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
From the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, by the way, numerous videos shot in use have already been uploaded to the platform, but this "genus" the British have only recently discovered for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less lifelike simulation.
