Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of relocating the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year will provide us with fewer such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood as "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and days off.
Unemployment days are mostly church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: Both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The national holidays are March 15, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August, the founding of the state, on the 1st of May the work is celebrated, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each for Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work a day before or after the holiday.
However, the price of the extended weekends is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is ultimately to be worked out, is determined for many years by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public employees and public servants alike.
Excluded are only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on holidays.
This year, the working rules are only slightly confused by the holidays at the end of the year: From December 24, life here in Germany will officially stop, since most people take the time offset for the days between Christmas and New Year’s Eve, or the specially suspended holiday.
Next year, there will be more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so that there will be fewer re-dispositions during the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a rest day.
The second rescheduling is related to the holiday on October 23: on Saturday, October 18, you will have to finish the Friday, October 24 in advance.
However, the end of the year will be completely marked by the holidays, after everything stops and stops from December 24, even if New Year’s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six deterrent little things to annoy colleagues
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive – harmless lies that we no longer notice: they bring “color” into everyday workplace life.
The only question is whether you get used to these small inconveniences, or whether you better face the challenge and try to avoid these misunderstandings, consciously for other annoying situations.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone called from the marketing department" - says a colleague.
Did you miss a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by perhaps calling the marketing department and confessing repentantly that you forgot to align the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, the case is dismissed with an apology.
Before you get caught up in embarrassing excuses, you should consider what you can really do to give your colleagues unpleasant moments and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Borrow something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s hardly anything more annoying than reaching for a document, office supplies, or phone, but it’s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost pen discovered on a colleague’s desk?
Without asking, you should not borrow anything from colleagues, because they are rightly angered when they find that something has gone wrong.
So, don't put envelopes or post-it from the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more there, if you really need it.
Talking about the private life of colleagues?
There is no effective way to stop a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who with whom, what done?
Where and why?
If possible, one should not tie the information (or assumptions) about the private life of the colleagues to the nose of everyone!
And if someone opens up and reveals his innermost secret to us, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, instead of directing the person who is not present, even if others are aware of the problems of the colleague.
Reported ill for no reason?
If you call the office to report yourself sick in reference to agonizing headaches, because you are feeling uncomfortable or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: your own work, unremitting tasks, projects with fixed deadlines now have to be done by your colleagues instead of you.
So don’t play bad with your colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you will not be able to get to the office the next day, or that something could get in the way, which is why you have to stay at home, you should report it in time so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
In the meantime, call, phone
You are deeply immersed in your work, but are suddenly disturbed by the loud jokes of your colleagues?
Did you hear a phone call that you shouldn’t have heard?
You should not annoy your colleagues with buzzing, singing, loud conversations (which you conduct over their heads), trampling, constantly scolding or nagging.
All of this can be very disturbing, even if they are not exactly immersed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Is it always the other people’s fault?
If a project is not completed on time, you have forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, you should not blame others for your own forgetfulness!
If possible, you should not talk about the chaos in the office or the loud colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others were affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake, or catch up with the missed, is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like home?
Workout pants and sleeping: Comfortable for at home, but hasn't lost anything in the office!
Not even then should you dress so casually if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself so much that you dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
