Cuba - most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday will come true if you choose only the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palms and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and enchanting cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
Only on one island, however, you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a warehouse or transit warehouse of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the bosses of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during the Prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were a.o.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, over the wide boulevards cars ran, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
Stars of the show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
Cocktails can be prepared at the bar at the Hotel Nacional.
And the cult cars of the fifties drive around in Havana to this day, because the once imported schigulis and fiats in the salty and humid air have long since fallen apart.
Havana, especially its oldest part, may have been heavily degraded, nowhere in the vicinity can you find so many wonderful colonial sights as right here.
Other places are just being refurbished, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have emerged not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba offers another maroon that is unique in the world and above all attracts railroad lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, so you can see neat and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long since been in the museum.
Excursions
The most important places are not missed by the majority of visitors to Cuba.
There is no need to write about Varadero or Havana.
It remains to be mentioned that there is a museum in the aforementioned Hemingways estate, whose visit should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on lime floor.
The Mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities accumulated fertile soil, through which even weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet it when you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the TV series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Fame and wealth brought her the trade of slaves and sugar.
The wealth was embodied in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed in four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that in the 1950s there was no road that would have connected the area with the rest of the country.
This isolation contributed to the fact that it was left unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, it is worthwhile to visit interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón Beach or the "Valley of Sugar Factory".
In the evening, you should go to the Casa de la Música, which revives after dark, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the eastern part of Cuba is described by some as the most beautiful of the island.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading to it from Guantánamo have to cross high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is barely touched by human intervention.
Thanks to its unspoilt nature, this eastern outpost of Cuba was included in the World Heritage List by UNESCO.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the Cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the voyages of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the present Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves confess, many pages could be written about all this.
As they say, it’s better to see with your own eyes.
