Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the International Space Station (ISS) crew will have taken more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is indispensable for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has achieved several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools embroidered by the astronauts to perform the repair.
The problem occurred on Wednesday when the astronauts unloaded the Harmony module from the Discovery space shuttle, a large cylindrical part that will soon accommodate European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module labs.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was to implement a 17.5-tonne module for generating electricity via solar panels, which was already on the ISS, in order to bring it to its final position.
After moving it, the crew went on to restructure the solar panels of the module, whose span is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be unfolded like accordions, was damaged by a jammed cable about a meter long.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to damage the collector any more.
The astronauts, who were originally to leave the Discovery space shuttle for a check-in and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to dedicate themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30-metre-long remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle that had been attached to the station to perform the repair.
He is one of NASA's best spacewalkers.
Large, resilient, very skilled, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
So the 46-year-old trained doctor was selected to operate the injured solar collector.
After carefully examining the damage, he cut the faulty cable and fastened a kind of rail on the damaged spot.
He was supported by a second Spacewalker who stayed near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini-hockey racket, wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar panels, which generate several hundred volts, had been conceived and crafted by the astronauts aboard the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited for the collector to be fully unfolded before counting his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before today seven astronauts returned to the Discovery space shuttle to take the expected return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
