A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen for a total length of 27 km, could not be viewed until now, unless with a humanitarian purpose, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. on the request of a former victim or his relatives.
In May 2006, the eleven governments – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct investigations, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health status of the forced labourers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The inmate lists of the concentration camps or the warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of personal inquiries in Bad Arolsen.
Nevertheless, a part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One cannot expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, explained Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
