Congress approves the MIFID policy, which entered into force on 1 November.
In parallel to the parliamentary drafting, which ended today with the Senate resolution on the amendments/additional amendments to the project, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law with the intention of allowing the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of congressmen and senators who, in their negotiations and votes, had sought to establish the best possible regulation that ensures the safety of investors and regulates individual business activities, thus guaranteeing a generally efficient market.
In addition to modernising the financial markets, MIFID seeks to improve investor protection, to increase the right of control of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and to promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive will allow for the provision of financial advice to specialised firms as well as to natural or legal persons, and will also contribute to the creation of new financial services firms (ESIS), which are consulting firms that merge with investment and brokerage firms of securities.
It also expands the number of financial transaction execution systems, adding to regulated circulation markets multilateral securities trading systems and trading order internationalization systems, which would eventually compete with current economic operators.
The law requires investment firms to disclose the priorities of their corporate profile, the confrontation and the forms of dealing with risks in the market and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV's control task.
The Congressional Economic Commission made further changes in retrospect, with the decision that the titled bond must now be considered complex financial means for the investor due to its high degree of risk has been confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crisis.
It also took advantage of the entry into force of the Directive on the legal delimitation of the working areas of graduate economists; 30 years after the 1977 Regulation restricting the working areas reserved for economists was adopted.
The Senate, for its part, established new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the economic mediator, who works on a foreign account, does not require authorization by the CNMV and can offer its services for commercialization of products and customer acquisition simultaneously to several investment companies.
