New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute stirs up between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be impaired.
The majority of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are directed through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU states.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom’s imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," Ukraine's economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] through Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This subsequently led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drastically raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for one-quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the world’s largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish state health service must improve the controls of criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of chief financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought to Scotland in connection with the June attack on Glasgow Airport.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish state health service had no exact idea of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The chief financial controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a SUV was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors to appear in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October, and was charged in connection with the alleged car bombing in Britain.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks prior to hiring foreign staff to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency does not have the authority to obtain this information outside of the UK.
The chief auditor’s report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should incorporate guidelines from the criminal records excerpt, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we have found indications of these checks in some personnel records, these were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would highly follow their investigative guidelines prior to hiring, but added, “Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information is available on the number of foreign health service employees.”
BMA Scotland chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations ahead of hiring potential NHS staff would identify people who might commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that the current pre-employment tests of the NHS Scotland are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards would have trouble identifying those employees who are on indefinite leave.
The investigation further found that established control procedures of NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian have been predominantly adhered to.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines on pre-employment controls for foreign personnel in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was my concern to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices would be reflected in updated guidelines regarding pre-employment control investigations by all staff, including those from abroad, whose publication is scheduled for next month.
