Climate on Venus could reveal an outlook on Earth’s future
Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft on an orbit show that the planet resembles a distant twin of Earth even more than was previously conscious.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, conditions on Venus would have been very similar to those on Earth and could even have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But due to the unbridled carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by sunlight, and a slower rotational rate, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency’s Venus Express spacecraft, which has been studying the plant for a year, offer a sobering look at how Earth could evolve in the face of catastrophic climate changes.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the heads of the Venus Express Mission, said: "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that of Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
"Our new data allows us to construct a scenario where Venus began billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment."
