Pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall into; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No noble titles seem to have been sold, no politician in Paris paid hotel bills, no extramarital toes sucked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has veiled donations to the British ruling Labour Party over more than <0xC2><0xA3>650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something without which the contested Gordon Brown would have done well.
Two months ago, when the prime minister had shunned the demand for an election, insulting the British intelligence in a silly way, claiming that opinion polls had not influenced that decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly shrewd representative chairman of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once feared Brown has evolved from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The inappropriate rescue of Northern Rock, a hit bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to amend the tax laws have upset corporate associations against the government.
The tax authorities’ loss of personal data of 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative cheating.
A trio of retired generals started an uprising in the upper house in protest against cuts in military spending: to be a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the manifold donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s secretary general (and her former executive director) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown is irrevocably heading for resignation.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a turning point after which they feel it is impossible to govern.
Neither do people like nor trust politicians, but they usually withhold their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that it is unlikely that a prime minister will improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there for long, this postponement is over: the public service is starting to leak; the cabinet ministers are starting to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown’s position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he wanted to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant.
The issues with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction records, for example, are related to decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's misfortunes -- like the long "money for titles" investigation of political party funding -- voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown's situation isn't quite as bad as it looks
The mistakes are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died, or was completely scammed.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown’s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid, and slightly brutal government.
The new campaign for political donations is a good example.
The garboesque Abraham, who compares his donations to his charitable gifts, says he wishes no public recognition for his benevolence.
It may be, but the decision was not his.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham’s agreement, but not that it is illegal, will of course have to ask himself a few questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour’s main fundraiser, who was told about the odd donations in October.
But so far, Brown has not been involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half of the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he diluted this determination by grabbing for a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject — to make the measure complete, from a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it's a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr. Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the Independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been unoccupied for six months, and moving forward with a thorough reform of political party funding.
This would require the hardliners of the Labour Party to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly abandon the special financial relationship with the unions – bitter pills for a partymate like Mr. Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve victory is through undeniable integrity and solid competence.
Card sharks
Is the credit crisis triggering America’s credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is only natural for spinal fins to swirl around excitedly.
Now that America’s real estate market is hurting, predators are targeting the country’s credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of contamination from underfunded credit spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both decommissioning and decommissioning rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are not repayable or are more than 30 days late in each case.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 billion fee collection from its U.S. consumer finances, partly due to the weakness of credit card holders.
It is still too early to panic.
Losses and delays are still low.
According to rating agency Moody, the third-quarter summary rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in U.S. private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt fall in bankruptcy filings, which in turn accounted for a large part of credit card losses; the number of filings (and thus default fees) would increase again whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
The industry also reports solid payment rates that show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month.
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, expects that spending in 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market: it is more likely that consumers are taking up credit card debt, now that home loans are drying out.
However, the card issuers look at the money flow rather than capital values, which is why falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower’s creditworthiness.
They can even be beneficial to card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates drop when the real estate is less value than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the more stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and completely reassess the loans,” says Gary Perlin, Capital One’s chief financial officer.
Even if a sudden undercover crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are considerably more real.
If lower home prices and a credit reduction push America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a grimer future.
Keep an eye out for these shark fins.
