Venus is the hellish twin of the Earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and windstorms at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that there is lightning on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has proved - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "original soup theory," lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms in the ocean are said to have stimulated reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
"If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history," Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington explains.
Today, there is hardly anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the devil's twin of the earth, but it is a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has undergone such a completely different evolution, is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, since since the early 1990s no probe has been on the way specifically to explore this planet.
The latest research, now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscores the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, according to the researchers.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with Earth are greater than initially thought," the ESA said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of airflows in the earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the Morning Star or Evening Star, orbits the Sun in almost 225 days.
But it revolves around itself much slower: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets originated under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost in space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
