He referred to the decision of the sports federation expected for the beginning of December on a Munich application for the 2018 Winter Games.
"This preference means for us that we will not have realistic opportunities until 2028 in the period previously envisaged by us."
However, the dream was not dreamed out for all time, von Beust said.
The Hamburger Sportbund (HSB) regretted the statements by Beusts.
This gives the impression that Hamburg will no longer compete for the Olympic Games in the next 25 years.
"It is too early to take a chance by burying the plans already at this time," HSB President Günter Ploß said on Wednesday.
Renouncing the application would also be in contradiction with the statement made by the head of the Senate on the occasion of a reception at the General Assembly of the General German Higher Education Sports Association.
There, von Beust described Hamburg’s application for the 2015 Universiade as “not a substitute” for the Olympic Games in Hamburg.
The university sports association had only last week nominated Hamburg as a candidate city.
The SPD Citizenship Group accused the Senate of not using valuable time for housing in Hamburg.
"The development of the Little Grasbrook has been delayed by the Senate for years because it put Olympia on the map and excluded housing," said SPD MPs Carola Veit and Jan Quast.
While the SPD has always called for an integrated planning for Olympia and a later housing use for the Little Grasbrook, the CDU has unilaterally opted for the "event factor".
The application for the 2012 Summer Olympics had sparked a lot of enthusiasm in Hamburg at the time.
Hamburg failed in Leipzig.
These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Anyone who combines the terms Sweden and wooden box thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Isn't it?
Currently, wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol’s work directory.
The majority of the ninety-four "type Stockholm" Brillo boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes of 1968 a few months ago, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now comes to a sobering result: The six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has probably given to the Moderna Museet in 1995 as a gift, are also available in Stockholm.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the soap powder "Brillo" cardboard boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at the time entered art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol-Brillo-Boxes with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at Moderna Museet, has examined not only the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, but also three from Swedish privately owned, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press chipboards were first primed and emeralded, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press chipboard with a paint roller without primer - in addition, it is not oil, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet, said: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced to investigate the "severe allegations" raised in respect of the soap-powder boxes.
Since then, however, they have been enveloped in relentless silence.
Rebel soldiers in Manila surrender
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers have given up, who have sheltered themselves in a Manila hotel and called for the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He cannot account for bloodshed, said Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, to reporters at the hotel.
Government loyal soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas use.
Around two dozen soldiers had been confined to the building for hours.
About half of them were on trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly stand down with about 30 sympathizers.
The military policemen who were supposed to guard him had apparently run over to him and joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula hotel and called for the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government forces locked the district around the prestigious hotel.
The president called for an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Advisor Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have enough," Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who formerly commanded the Scout Rangers’ elite unit, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
Government critics had called for major demonstrations against the president for Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by corruption allegations for months.
Manila's financial district was the main scene of the attempted mutiny of some 200 military personnel against Arroyo as early as 2003.
The uprising failed after almost 24 hours due to the army's refusal to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes major shareholder at Versatel
United Internet has secured a share of more than 20 percent in the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as the company announced on Wednesday evening.
It now holds 20.05 percent of the share capital.
A takeover had previously been speculated.
The option remains open to increasing the share of Versatel.
The move aims to advance the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet said.
Previously, on Wednesday, there had already been suspicions about an entry, after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf-based network operator by another 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The money house considers the shares to be only a third party, it said in the financial market.
The day before, United Internet had already taken a share of almost 10 percent in the mobile telephony company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares worth <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>106.4 million.
United has purchased 5.15 million shares for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>31.4 million.
In addition, the companies have started discussions on marketing cooperations for DSL and mobile products.
"We are strengthening our partnership," said a United Internet spokesperson.
The two companies founded the joint venture MSP to take over its competitor Freenet.
For now, the two companies want to settle for just over ten percent of Freenet and not make use of their right to acquire another 18.49 percent of Freenet, United Internet said on Thursday.
The two companies, however, remained open to all options, in particular also to further increase the stake in Freenet AG, it said.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership had ended in mid-November.
The poker around Freenet, which has been running for months and is difficult to see, is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
At the end of the third quarter, Freenet had 2.9 million mobile contract customers and 1.27 million DSL and complete connection customers.
The holding of United Internet and Drillisch so far held directly 6.01 percent of the Freenet shares.
Now it has been agreed that Drillisch will bring in another four percent.
The right to buy the 18.49 percent from the investment company Vatas had already been agreed in August.
